> Despite their name, sunchokes, aka Jerusalem artichokes, have nothing at all to do with Jerusalem and are not, in fact, artichokes. When thinly sliced and roasted, sunchokes become irresistibly crispy and pair perfectly with hearty kale and quinoa.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. In a small #pot, bring @water{1 1/2%cups} and a large pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil. Thinly slice the @sunchokes{6%ounce} into rounds. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Place in the oven for about ~{20%minutes}, flipping once, until golden brown and crispy.

Cook the quinoa: Meanwhile, add the @quinoa{3/4%cup} to the boiling water. Cover and reduce to a simmer for ~{15%minutes}, until tender.

Remove and discard the kale ribs and stems before coarsely chopping the leaves. Thinly slice the @scallions{2}(thinly sliced), keeping the greens and whites separate. Pick then coarsely chop the @mint{1/4%ounce}(coarsely chopped) leaves.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1/2%tsp} in a large pan over medium heat. Add the @Tuscan kale{4%ounce}. Cook, tossing, for ~{3-4%minutes}, until tender. If necessary, add a splash of @water{splash} to help speed up the process.

When the quinoa is ready, toss it in a large #bowl{} with the scallion whites, mint, kale, @feta cheese{1/4%cup}, 1/2 tablespoon @white wine vinegar{1/2%tbsp}, and a large drizzle of @olive oil{2 1/2%tsp}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Serve: Plate the quinoa salad and top with the crispy sunchokes. Garnish with the scallion greens and @dried cranberries{1%ounce}. Enjoy!